# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacteroidota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:bacteroidota/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:bacteroidota/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:bacteroidota/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:bacteroidota/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bacteroidota/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bacteroidota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:bacteroidota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Although some *Bacteroides* spp. can be opportunistic pathogens, many *Bacteroidota* are symbiotic species highly adjusted to the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] *Bacteroides* are highly abundant in intestines, reaching up to 1011 cells g−1 of intestinal material.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] They perform metabolic conversions that are essential for the host, such as degradation of proteins or complex sugar polymers.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] *Bacteroidota* colonize the gastrointestinal tract already in infants, as non-digestible oligosaccharides in mother milk support the growth of both *Bacteroides* and *Bifidobacterium* spp.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] *Bacteroides* spp. are selectively recognized by the immune system of the host through specific interactions.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] For a long time, it was thought that the majority of Gram-negative gastrointestinal tract bacteria belonged to the genus *Bacteroides*, but in recent years many species of *Bacteroides* have undergone reclassification.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Based on current classification, the majority of the gastrointestinal *Bacteroidota* species belong to the families *Bacteroidaceae*, *Prevotellaceae*, *Rikenellaceae*, and *Porphyromonadaceae*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] This phylum is sometimes grouped with *Chlorobiota*, *Fibrobacterota*, *Gemmatimonadota*, *Calditrichota*, and marine group A to form the FCB group or superphylum.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] In the alternative classification system proposed by Cavalier-Smith, this taxon is instead a class in the phylum Sphingobacteria.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] In the gastrointestinal microbiota *Bacteroidota* have a very broad metabolic potential and are regarded as one of the most stable part of gastrointestinal microflora.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Reduced abundance of the *Bacteroidota* in some cases is associated with obesity.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] This bacterial group as a whole has conflicting evidence for alteration of abundance in patients with irritable bowel syndrome, though its genus *Bacteroides* is likely enriched, but it may be involved in type 1 and type 2 diabetes pathogenesis.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] *Bacteroides* spp. in contrast to *Prevotella* spp. were recently found to be enriched in the metagenomes of subjects with low gene richness that were associated with adiposity, insulin resistance and dyslipidaemia as well as an inflammatory phenotype.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] *Bacteroidota* species that belong to classes *Flavobacteriales* and *Sphingobacteriales* are typical soil bacteria and are only occasionally detected in the gastrointestinal tract, except *Capnocytophaga spp.* and *Sphingobacterium spp.* that can be detected in the human oral cavity.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Gastrointestinal *Bacteroidota* species produce succinic acid, acetic acid, and in some cases propionic acid, as the major end-products.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Species belonging to the genera *Alistipes*, *Bacteroides*, *Parabacteroides*, *Prevotella*, *Paraprevotella*, *Alloprevotella*, *Barnesiella*, and *Tannerella* are saccharolytic, while species belonging to *Odoribacter* and *Porphyromonas* are predominantly asaccharolytic.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Some *Bacteroides spp.* and *Prevotella spp.* can degrade complex plant polysaccharides such as starch, cellulose, xylans, and pectins.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] The *Bacteroidota* species also play an important role in protein metabolism by proteolytic activity assigned to the proteases linked to the cell.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Some "*Bacteroides* spp. have a potential to utilize urea as a nitrogen source.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Other important functions of *Bacteroides* spp. include the deconjugation of bile acids and growth on mucus.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Many members of the *Bacteroidota* genera (*Flexibacter*, *Cytophaga*, *Sporocytophaga* and relatives) are coloured yellow-orange to pink-red due to the presence of pigments of the flexirubin group.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] In some *Bacteroidota* strains, flexirubins may be present together with carotenoid pigments.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Carotenoid pigments are usually found in marine and halophilic members of the group, whereas flexirubin pigments are more frequent in clinical, freshwater or soil-colonizing representatives.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Comparative genomic analysis has led to the identification of 27 proteins which are present in most species of the phylum *Bacteroidota*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Of these, one protein is found in all sequenced *Bacteroidota* species, while two other proteins are found in all sequenced species with the exception of those from the genus *Bacteroides*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] The absence of these two proteins in this genus is likely due to selective gene loss.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Additionally, four proteins have been identified which are present in all *Bacteroidota* species except *Cytophaga hutchinsonii*; this is again likely due to selective gene loss.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] A further eight proteins have been identified which are present in all sequenced *Bacteroidota* genomes except *Salinibacter ruber*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] The absence of these proteins may be due to selective gene loss, or because *S. ruber* branches very deeply, the genes for these proteins may have evolved after the divergence of *S. ruber*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] A conserved signature indel has also been identified; this three-amino-acid deletion in ClpB chaperone is present in all species of the *Bacteroidota* phylum except *S. ruber*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] This deletion is also found in one *Chlorobiota* species and one *Archaeum* species, which is likely due to horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] These 27 proteins and the three-amino-acid deletion serve as molecular markers for the *Bacteroidota*.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Species from the *Bacteroidota* and *Chlorobiota* phyla branch very closely together in phylogenetic trees, indicating a close relationship.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Through the use of comparative genomic analysis, three proteins have been identified which are uniquely shared by virtually all members of the *Bacteroidota* and *Chlorobiota* phyla.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] The sharing of these three proteins is significant because other than them, no proteins from either the *Bacteroidota* or *Chlorobiota* phyla are shared by any other groups of bacteria.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Several conserved signature indels have also been identified which are uniquely shared by members of the phyla.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] The presence of these molecular signatures supports their close relationship.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Additionally, the phylum *Fibrobacterota* is indicated to be specifically related to these two phyla.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] A clade consisting of these three phyla is strongly supported by phylogenetic analyses based upon a number of different proteins These phyla also branch in the same position based upon conserved signature indels in a number of important proteins.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] Lastly and most importantly, two conserved signature indels (in the RpoC protein and in serine hydroxymethyltransferase) and one signature protein PG00081 have been identified that are uniquely shared by all of the species from these three phyla.
[src:bacteroidota/bacteroidota] All of these results provide compelling evidence that the species from these three phyla shared a common ancestor exclusive of all other bacteria, and it has been proposed that they should all recognized as part of a single "FCB" superphylum.
